# Code Formatting — Blank Lines

## One blank line between logical sections

Use **exactly one** blank line between major sections (import groups, top-level functions/classes, unrelated blocks). **Never** use two or more consecutive blank lines.

This overrides PEP 8’s “two blank lines before top-level `def`/`class`”—use **one**.

## No blank line: decorator → definition

A decorator must sit **directly above** the `def`, `async def`, or `class` it applies to—**no blank line** between them.

```python
# ✅ Good
@router.post("/", status_code=201)
def create_order(...):
    ...

@dataclass
class InsertOneResult:
    ...
```

```python
# ❌ Bad
@router.post("/", status_code=201)

def create_order(...):
    ...
```

Applies to `@router.*`, `@pytest.fixture`, `@pytest.mark.parametrize`, `@dataclass`, `@asynccontextmanager`, and any other decorator.

## Same-nature module-level variables stay grouped

Related constants/config at module level (e.g. `JWT_*` in `config.py`) belong in one block **without** blank lines between them. Use one blank line before/after the whole block to separate it from imports or functions.

## File endings — no trailing newline

The file must end on the **last character of the last line of code**. Do **not** add:

- a trailing empty line after the last statement, or
- a final newline character (`\n`) after the last line

In the editor, the cursor should not sit on an extra blank line below the last line of code. When saving or generating files, use `.rstrip("\n")` so the EOF has zero newline bytes.

```python
# ✅ Good — file ends immediately after last line
db = client["assetManager"]
```

```python
# ❌ Bad — extra newline creates a visible blank line in the editor
db = client["assetManager"]
<EOF newline here>
```

## Import groups

Keep stdlib → third-party → local groups with **one** blank line between groups—not two.

## Inside functions

Use at most **one** blank line between logical steps; no stacked empty lines.
